NeuroScreen AI | User & Clinical Manual
System Version: 3.0.4 (2026 Build)
1. PRODUCT OVERVIEW
NeuroScreen is a state-of-the-art AI-driven clinical diagnostic tool designed for the early-stage detection of dementia and related cognitive impairments. By combining traditional neurological assessment frameworks with neural analysis and multi-language Speech-to-Text (STT) and Text-to-Speech (TTS) technology, NeuroScreen provides immediate risk profiling for clinical environments.

2. GETTING STARTED
2.1 Hardware Requirements
Audio Input: High-fidelity microphone for voice recognition.

Audio Output: Speakers or headphones for automated question narration.

Display: Minimum resolution of 1024x768 for clinical reports.

Connectivity: Stable internet connection for Tailwind and FontAwesome CDN assets.

2.2 Launching the Application
Open the index.html file in any modern web browser (Chrome, Edge, or Safari).

The Hero Section will initialize. This is the "Stable UI" zone where you can view the primary call-to-action.

3. CORE FUNCTIONALITIES
3.1 Language Personalization
NeuroScreen supports five primary clinical languages. This is managed via the Language Selector in the navigation bar.

English: Default (en-US)

Hindi: (hi-IN)

French: (fr-FR)

Spanish: (es-ES)

German: (de-DE)

Note: Changing the language updates the UI text, the diagnostic question set, and the AI Voice Narration accent.

3.2 Patient Registration
Before an assessment begins, clinical staff must enter patient metadata:

Full Name and Age.

Contact details (Email/Phone).

Medical History (Diabetes, Hypertension, Family History).
This data is stored in the local session for report generation.

3.3 The Diagnostic Flow (15 Steps)
The assessment is divided into three distinct neurological phases:

Phase 1: Orientation (Questions 1–5)

Tests the patient's awareness of time and place.

AI speaks the question; the patient answers via text or voice.

Phase 2: Word Memory (Questions 6–10)

A randomized set of 5 words is presented and read aloud.

The patient must memorize them during a "Cooldown" phase.

The patient is later asked to recall these words.

Phase 3: Numerical Recall (Questions 11–15)

Tests short-term working memory and concentration.

Uses randomized 2-digit number sequences.

4. ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY
4.1 AI Voice Narration (TTS)
The system automatically reads out every question. This ensures accessibility for patients with visual impairments or literacy challenges. The voice will automatically match the selected language's native accent.

4.2 Voice Input (STT)
Click the Microphone Icon in the input field to enable Speech-to-Text. The patient can speak their answer, which the AI will transcribe into the text field for processing.

